{"id":"1506.08837","submitter":"Jan Kolodynski","authors":"Remigiusz Augusiak, Jan Kolodynski, Alexander Streltsov, Manabendra\n  Nath Bera, Antonio Acin, Maciej Lewenstein","title":"Asymptotic role of entanglement in quantum metrology","comments":"12 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 94, 012339 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.94.012339","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum systems allow one to sense physical parameters beyond the reach of\nclassical statistics---with resolutions greater than $1/N$, where $N$ is the\nnumber of constituent particles independently probing a parameter. In the\ncanonical phase sensing scenario the \\emph{Heisenberg Limit} $1/N^{2}$ may be\nreached, which requires, as we show, both the relative size of the largest\nentangled block and the geometric measure of entanglement to be nonvanishing as\n$N\\to\\infty$. Yet, we also demonstrate that in the asymptotic $N$ limit any\nprecision scaling arbitrarily close to the Heisenberg Limit\n($1/N^{2-\\varepsilon}$ with any $\\varepsilon>0$) may be attained, even though\nthe system gradually becomes noisier and separable, so that both the above\nentanglement quantifiers asymptotically vanish. Our work shows that\nsufficiently large quantum systems achieve nearly optimal resolutions despite\ntheir relative amount of entanglement being arbitrarily small. In deriving our\nresults, we establish the continuity relation of the quantum Fisher information\nevaluated for a phaselike parameter, which lets us link it directly to the\ngeometry of quantum states, and hence naturally to the geometric measure of\nentanglement.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Jun 2015 20:02:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 24 Feb 2016 11:22:20 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 22 Jul 2016 20:23:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-07-26"}
